&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/once-said-by-the-wise/Once_Said_By_The_Wise-The_Gloomy_Sunday_Hungarian_Suicide_Song.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p style="text-align: justify;"><a title="Birling Gap" rel="nofollow" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/11984133@N05/4339093574/" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft" style="border: 0pt none;" src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4036/4339093574_a1da9a3b6f_m.jpg" border="0" alt="Up Quotes: Glooming Sunday" width="240" height="160" /></a>I became conscious about this old controversial suicide song entitled “Gloomy Sunday” when my uncle told me that he felt dizzy after He heard this song.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Gloomy Sunday&#8221; is a song composed by an Hungarian pianist and composer Rezső Seress in 1933 written by László Jávor with the original Hungarian title of both song and poem &#8220;Szomorú vasárnap” in which the soloist reflects on the horrors of modern way of life.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Despite the fact that it was recorded and performed by many soloists, &#8220;Gloomy Sunday&#8221; is very much related with Billie Holiday, who scored a batter version of the song in 1941. Due to unsubstantiated urban folklore about its inspiring hundreds of suicides, &#8220;Gloomy Sunday&#8221; was dubbed the &#8220;Hungarian suicide song&#8221; in the United States. Seress did commit suicide in 1968 after hearing and revising this song, based on rumors, the song was being banned from radio. Due to the context of the Second World War, Billie Holiday&#8217;s version was banned by also by the BBC. There have been numerous urban legends concerning the song over the years, mostly involving it being purportedly linked with various numbers of suicides, and many radio networks reacted by allegedly banning the song on their stations. However, most of these claims are still unsubstantiated.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Other critics said that the rumors have no strong supporting evidences<sup> </sup>about the sparking suicides. They conclude that this was a merely deliberate marketing campaign in order to make the song popular and have lots of copy in the market. But still now it is a unsolved mystery why the maker of this song Rezső Seress killed himself after composing “Gloomy Sunday”.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><object classid="clsid:d27cdb6e-ae6d-11cf-96b8-444553540000" width="300" height="250" codebase="http://download.macromedia.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=6,0,40,0"><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true" /><param name="allowscriptaccess" value="always" /><param name="src" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/48cTUnUtzx4?fs=1&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0&amp;color1=0x006699&amp;color2=0x54abd6" /><param name="allowfullscreen" value="true" /><embed type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="300" height="250" src="http://www.youtube.com/v/48cTUnUtzx4?fs=1&amp;hl=en_US&amp;rel=0&amp;color1=0x006699&amp;color2=0x54abd6" allowscriptaccess="always" allowfullscreen="true"></embed></object></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>Gloomy Sunday (Literal English Translation)</strong></p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Gloomy Sunday with a hundred white flowers<br />
I was waiting for you my dearest with a prayer<br />
A Sunday morning, chasing after my dreams<br />
The carriage of my sorrow returned to me without you<br />
It is since then that my Sundays have been forever sad<br />
Tears my only drink, the sorrow my bread&#8230;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">Gloomy Sunday</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">This last Sunday, my darling please come to me<br />
There will be a priest, a coffin, a catafalque and a winding-sheet<br />
There wi&#8217;ll be flowers for you, flowers and a coffin<br />
Under the blossoming trees it will be my last journey<br />
My eyes will be open, so that I could see you for a last time<br />
Don&#8217;t be afraid of my eyes, I&#8217;m blessing you even in my death&#8230;<br />
The last Sunday</p>
